<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="534" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,639,194,1357]" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,273,964,985]" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith and Paulsen" authorityYear="2017" box="[282,448,963,985]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Podolasia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diabla">
<emphasis box="[282,448,963,985]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">Podolasia diabla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species in the genus to possess horns on the head. Despite the small size of the only known specimen, the horns are well developed. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith and Paulsen" authorityYear="2017" box="[401,564,1043,1065]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Podolasia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diabla">
<emphasis box="[401,564,1043,1065]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">Podolasia diabla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
keys to 
<taxonomicName authority="Howden, 1954" authorityName="Howden" authorityYear="1954" box="[151,455,1069,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Podolasia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[151,311,1069,1091]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">Podolasia pilosa</emphasis>
Howden, 1954
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Howden, H. F." box="[483,634,1070,1091]" pageId="2" pageNumber="534" pagination="275 - 277" refId="ref2360" refString="Howden, H. F. 1997. Podolasiini Howden, new tribe, When describing the tribe Podolasiini, Howden and a revision of the included genera, Podolasia (1997) provided a list of other &quot; primitive &quot; melo- Harold and Podostena Howden, new genus (Colonthine taxa that shared some characters. One leoptera: Scarabaeidae: Melolonthinae). The Coadditional character that we observed and warrants leopterists Bulletin 51: 223 - 255. mention is the sclerotized male genital capsule (Fig. Howden, H. F. 1998. More on Podolasia Harold: a new 9). This structure has two apical knobs with forward species and notes on another (Coleoptera: Scarprojecting setae, which is remarkable for a taxon in abaeidae: Melolonthinae). The Coleopterists Bulthe phytophagous scarab clade (Smith et al. 2006). letin 52: 275 - 277." type="journal article" year="1997">Howden (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, but it is easily distinguished from both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Howden" authorityYear="1954" box="[552,638,1096,1118]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Podolasia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[552,564,1097,1118]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[580,638,1096,1118]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith and Paulsen" authorityName="Smith and Paulsen" authorityYear="2017" box="[193,587,1123,1145]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Podolasia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parapilosa">
<emphasis box="[193,399,1123,1145]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">Podolasia parapilosa</emphasis>
Smith and Paulsen
</taxonomicName>
, new species by the head horns and the subcircular head with nearly continuous clypeal and genal margins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="534" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,639,194,1357]" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,290,1230,1251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">Etymology.</emphasis>
We name this species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith and Paulsen" authorityYear="2017" box="[531,592,1229,1251]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Podolasia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diabla">
<emphasis box="[531,592,1229,1251]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="534">diabla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the feminine form of the Spanish word for “devil”, in regards to the small horns that are unique in the tribe and rarely found in the subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[493,634,1309,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Melolonthinae</taxonomicName>
. This name should be treated as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
